issue.title: How to properly redirect www.* to non www

labels.name: kind/support
labels.description: Categorizes issue or PR as a support question.

labels.name: lifecycle/rotten
labels.description: Denotes an issue or PR that has aged beyond stale and will be auto-closed.

issue.body:
Currently on my GCE ingress, www.* does not get routed anywhere based on our configs. How do I set my ingress such that www.* get's routed to a particular service?

```
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: { .Values.ingressName }}
  annotations:
    kubernetes.io/ingress.class: "gce"
...
spec:
  rules: 
  - host: {{ .Values.web.host }}
    http:
      paths:
      - path: /*
        pathType: ImplementationSpecific
        backend:
          service:
            name: web-service
            port:
              number: {{ .Values.web.port }}
```

comment.body:
> Did you ever find a solution for this issue? I am facing the same thing. With nginx ingress there is just an annotation but for gce.....

Found anything?

* Initialize a logger instance in cmd/glbc/main.go.
* All ingress controller log messages will be prefixed by `IngressController`. 
  Example:
```
I1026 22:33:01.214618 2870049 controller.go:162] "IngressController: Ingress added, enqueuing" ingress="default/neg-demo-ing"
...
I1026 22:33:01.215184 2870049 controller.go:615] "IngressController: Syncing ingress" ingress="default/neg-demo-ing"
...
I1026 22:33:01.215264 2870049 controller.go:392] "IngressController: Skip syncing instance groups for ingress" ingressNamespace="default" ing  ressName="neg-demo-ing"
```
* Logging for sub-components like HealthChecker will be added in separate PRs.

comment.body:
Being honest, personally I don't like switch statements, because I always confused do we need to put breaks (I just google, in golang you don't need), and somehow because they are rarely used, it makes it's harder for me to read

Also for me switch is more like simple 1:1 mapping (though it would still work for this case), but we want to return NEGHealthCheck only if it is not ILB, and this would be confusing to read and understand in switch statement, and could result in a bug if we change order in switch (which is a bit unexpected to me)

pull_request.title: Gate ssa
pull_request.body:
Use `enableStrongSessionAffinity` flag to close access to Strong Session Affinity feature if not needed. 

This change includes: 
* @mmamczur commit 
* my changes to use excisting flag for SSA

Both of commits will be squashed together just before merging. 


That approach is called feature flagging. 
I found an article with more info about it: https://arxiv.org/pdf/1907.06157.pdf
